# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: memory-tagging-extension
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Due to their low costs, low power consumption, and low heat generation, ARM processors are useful for light, portable, battery-powered devices, including smartphones, laptops, and tablet computers, as well as embedded systems.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] However, ARM processors are also used for desktops and servers, including Fugaku, the world's fastest supercomputer from 2020 to 2022.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] With over 230 billion ARM chips produced, since at least 2003, and with its dominance increasing every year, ARM is the most widely used family of instruction set architectures.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] There have been several generations of the ARM design.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original ARM1 used a 32-bit internal structure but had a 26-bit address space that limited it to 64 MB of main memory.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This limitation was removed in the ARMv3 series, which has a 32-bit address space, and several additional generations up to ARMv7 remained 32-bit.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Released in 2011, the ARMv8-A architecture added support for a 64-bit address space and 64-bit arithmetic with its new 32-bit fixed-length instruction set.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings has also released a series of additional instruction sets for different roles: the "Thumb" extensions add both 32- and 16-bit instructions for improved code density, while Jazelle added instructions for directly handling Java bytecode.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] More recent changes include the addition of simultaneous multithreading (SMT) for improved performance or fault tolerance.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn Computers' first widely successful design was the BBC Micro, introduced in December 1981.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This was a relatively conventional machine based on the MOS Technology 6502 CPU but ran at roughly double the performance of competing designs like the Apple II due to its use of faster dynamic random-access memory (DRAM).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Typical DRAM of the era ran at about 2 MHz; Acorn arranged a deal with Hitachi for a supply of faster 4 MHz parts.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Machines of the era generally shared memory between the processor and the framebuffer, which allowed the processor to quickly update the contents of the screen without having to perform separate input/output (I/O).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] As the timing of the video display is exacting, the video hardware had to have priority access to that memory.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Due to a quirk of the 6502's design, the CPU left the memory untouched for half of the time.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Thus by running the CPU at 1 MHz, the video system could read data during those down times, taking up the total 2 MHz bandwidth of the RAM.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In the BBC Micro, the use of 4 MHz RAM allowed the same technique to be used, but running at twice the speed.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This allowed it to outperform any similar machine on the market.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] 1981 was also the year that the IBM Personal Computer was introduced.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Using the recently introduced Intel 8088, a 16-bit CPU compared to the 6502's 8-bit design, it offered higher overall performance.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Its introduction changed the desktop computer market radically: what had been largely a hobby and gaming market emerging over the prior five years began to change to a must-have business tool where the earlier 8-bit designs simply could not compete.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Even newer 32-bit designs were also coming to market, such as the Motorola 68000 and National Semiconductor NS32016.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn began considering how to compete in this market and produced a new paper design named the Acorn Business Computer.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] They set themselves the goal of producing a machine with ten times the performance of the BBC Micro, but at the same price.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This would outperform and underprice the PC.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] At the same time, the recent introduction of the Apple Lisa brought the graphical user interface (GUI) concept to a wider audience and suggested the future belonged to machines with a GUI.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Lisa, however, cost $9,995, as it was packed with support chips, large amounts of memory, and a hard disk drive, all very expensive then.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The engineers then began studying all of the CPU designs available.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Their conclusion about the existing 16-bit designs was that they were a lot more expensive and were still "a bit crap", offering only slightly higher performance than their BBC Micro design.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] They also almost always demanded a large number of support chips to operate even at that level, which drove up the cost of the computer as a whole.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] These systems would simply not hit the design goal.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] They also considered the new 32-bit designs, but these cost even more and had the same issues with support chips.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] According to Sophie Wilson, all the processors tested at that time performed about the same, with about a 4 Mbit/s bandwidth.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Two key events led Acorn down the path to ARM.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] One was the publication of a series of reports from the University of California, Berkeley, which suggested that a simple chip design could nevertheless have extremely high performance, much higher than the latest 32-bit designs on the market.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The second was a visit by Steve Furber and Sophie Wilson to the Western Design Center, a company run by Bill Mensch and his sister Kathryn, which had become the logical successor to the MOS team and was offering new versions like the WDC 65C02.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Acorn team saw high school students producing chip layouts on Apple II machines, which suggested that anyone could do it.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In contrast, a visit to another design firm working on modern 32-bit CPU revealed a team with over a dozen members who were already on revision H of their design and yet it still contained bugs.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This cemented their late 1983 decision to begin their own CPU design, the Acorn RISC Machine.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original Berkeley RISC designs were in some sense teaching systems, not designed specifically for outright performance.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] To the RISC's basic register-heavy and load/store concepts, ARM added a number of the well-received design notes of the 6502.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Primary among them was the ability to quickly service interrupts, which allowed the machines to offer reasonable input/output performance with no added external hardware.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] To offer interrupts with similar performance as the 6502, the ARM design limited its physical address space to 64 MB of total addressable space, requiring 26 bits of address.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] As instructions were 4 bytes (32 bits) long, and required to be aligned on 4-byte boundaries, the lower 2 bits of an instruction address were always zero.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This meant the program counter (PC) only needed to be 24 bits, allowing it to be stored along with the eight bit processor flags in a single 32-bit register.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] That meant that upon receiving an interrupt, the entire machine state could be saved in a single operation, whereas had the PC been a full 32-bit value, it would require separate operations to store the PC and the status flags.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This decision halved the interrupt overhead.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Another change, and among the most important in terms of practical real-world performance, was the modification of the instruction set to take advantage of page mode DRAM.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Recently introduced, page mode allowed subsequent accesses of memory to run twice as fast if they were roughly in the same location, or "page", in the DRAM chip.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Berkeley's design did not consider page mode and treated all memory equally.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM design added special vector-like memory access instructions, the "S-cycles", that could be used to fill or save multiple registers in a single page using page mode.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This doubled memory performance when they could be used, and was especially important for graphics performance.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The Berkeley RISC designs used register windows to reduce the number of register saves and restores performed in procedure calls; the ARM design did not adopt this.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson developed the instruction set, writing a simulation of the processor in BBC BASIC that ran on a BBC Micro with a second 6502 processor.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This convinced Acorn engineers they were on the right track.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson approached Acorn's CEO, Hermann Hauser, and requested more resources.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Hauser gave his approval and assembled a small team to design the actual processor based on Wilson's instruction set architecture.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The official Acorn RISC Machine project started in October 1983.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn chose VLSI Technology as the "silicon partner", as they were a source of ROMs and custom chips for Acorn.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Acorn provided the design and VLSI provided the layout and production.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first samples of ARM silicon worked properly when first received and tested on 26 April 1985.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Known as ARM1, these versions ran at 6 MHz.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first ARM application was as a second processor for the BBC Micro, where it helped in developing simulation software to finish development of the support chips (VIDC, IOC, MEMC), and sped up the CAD software used in ARM2 development.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Wilson subsequently rewrote BBC BASIC in ARM assembly language.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The in-depth knowledge gained from designing the instruction set enabled the code to be very dense, making ARM BBC BASIC an extremely good test for any ARM emulator.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM Evaluations Systems featuring ARM1 CPUs and supplied as second processors for BBC Micro and Master machines, were made available from July 1986 under the Acorn OEM Products brand to developers and researchers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The A500 Second Processor, an additional ARM1 based BBC Micro and Master second processor, featured the ARM support chipset (VIDC, IOC, MEMC), was capable of producing video output and operating near independently of the host BBC Micro.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The result of the simulations on the ARM1 boards led to the late 1986 introduction of the ARM2 design running at 8 MHz, and the early 1987 speed-bumped version at 10 to 12 MHz.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] A significant change in the underlying architecture was the addition of a Booth multiplier, whereas formerly multiplication had to be carried out in software.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Further, a new Fast Interrupt reQuest mode, FIQ for short, allowed registers 8 to 14 to be replaced as part of the interrupt itself.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This meant FIQ requests did not have to save out their registers, further speeding interrupts.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The first use of the ARM2 was in internal Acorn A500 development machines, and the Acorn Archimedes personal computer models A305, A310, and A440, launched on the 6th June 1987.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] According to the Dhrystone benchmark, the ARM2 was roughly seven times the performance of a typical 7 MHz 68000-based system like the Amiga or Macintosh SE.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] It was twice as fast as an Intel 80386 running at 16 MHz, and about the same speed as a multi-processor VAX-11/784 superminicomputer.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The only systems that beat it were the Sun SPARC and MIPS R2000 RISC-based workstations.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Further, as the CPU was designed for high-speed I/O, it dispensed with many of the support chips seen in these machines; notably, it lacked any dedicated direct memory access (DMA) controller which was often found on workstations.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The graphics system was also simplified based on the same set of underlying assumptions about memory and timing.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The result was a dramatically simplified design, offering performance on par with expensive workstations but at a price point similar to contemporary desktops.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM2 featured a 32-bit data bus, 26-bit address space and 27 32-bit registers, of which 16 are accessible at any one time (including the PC).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM2 had a transistor count of just 30,000, compared to Motorola's six-year-older 68000 model with around 68,000.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Much of this simplicity came from the lack of microcode, which represents about one-quarter to one-third of the 68000's transistors, and the lack of (like most CPUs of the day) a cache.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This simplicity enabled the ARM2 to have a low power consumption and simpler thermal packaging by having fewer powered transistors.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Nevertheless, ARM2 offered better performance than the contemporary 1987 IBM PS/2 Model 50, which initially utilised an Intel 80286, offering 1.8 MIPS @ 10 MHz, and later in 1987, the 2 MIPS of the PS/2 70, with its Intel 386 DX @ 16 MHz.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] A successor, ARM3, was produced with a 4 KB cache, which further improved performance.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The address bus was extended to 32 bits in the ARM6, but program code still had to lie within the first 64 MB of memory in 26-bit compatibility mode, due to the reserved bits for the status flags.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1988, Sanyo became a worldwide second source for the ARM2 and associated chipset under an agreement with VLSI Technology.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In the late 1980s, Apple Computer and VLSI Technology started working with Acorn on newer versions of the ARM core.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1990, Acorn spun off the design team into a new company named Advanced RISC Machines Ltd., which became ARM Ltd. when its parent company, Arm Holdings plc, floated on the London Stock Exchange and Nasdaq in 1998.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The new Apple–ARM work would eventually evolve into the ARM6, first released in early 1992.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Apple used the ARM6-based ARM610 as the basis for their Apple Newton PDA.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 1994, Acorn used the ARM610 as the main central processing unit (CPU) in their RiscPC computers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] DEC licensed the ARMv4 architecture and produced the StrongARM.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] At 233 MHz, this CPU drew only one watt (newer versions draw far less).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This work was later passed to Intel as part of a lawsuit settlement, and Intel took the opportunity to supplement their i960 line with the StrongARM.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Intel later developed its own high performance implementation named XScale, which it has since sold to Marvell.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Transistor count of the ARM core remained essentially the same throughout these changes; ARM2 had 30,000 transistors, while ARM6 grew only to 35,000.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2005, about 98% of all mobile phones sold used at least one ARM processor.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2010, producers of chips based on ARM architectures reported shipments of 6.1 billion ARM-based processors, representing 95% of smartphones, 35% of digital televisions and set-top boxes, and 10% of mobile computers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2011, the 32-bit ARM architecture was the most widely used architecture in mobile devices and the most popular 32-bit one in embedded systems.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2013, 10 billion were produced and "ARM-based chips are found in nearly 60 percent of the world's mobile devices".
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings's primary business is selling IP cores, which licensees use to create microcontrollers (MCUs), CPUs, and systems-on-chips based on those cores.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The original design manufacturer combines the ARM core with other parts to produce a complete device, typically one that can be built in existing semiconductor fabrication plants (fabs) at low cost and still deliver substantial performance.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The most successful implementation has been the ARM7TDMI with hundreds of millions sold.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Atmel has been a precursor design center in the ARM7TDMI-based embedded system.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] The ARM architectures used in smartphones, PDAs and other mobile devices range from ARMv5 to ARMv8-A.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2009, some manufacturers introduced netbooks based on ARM architecture CPUs, in direct competition with netbooks based on Intel Atom.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings offers a variety of licensing terms, varying in cost and deliverables.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings provides to all licensees an integratable hardware description of the ARM core as well as complete software development toolset (compiler, debugger, software development kit), and the right to sell manufactured silicon containing the ARM CPU.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] SoC packages integrating ARM's core designs include Nvidia Tegra's first three generations, CSR plc's Quatro family, ST-Ericsson's Nova and NovaThor, Silicon Labs's Precision32 MCU, Texas Instruments's OMAP products, Samsung's Hummingbird and Exynos products, Apple's A4, A5, and A5X, and NXP's i.MX.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Fabless licensees, who wish to integrate an ARM core into their own chip design, are usually only interested in acquiring a ready-to-manufacture verified semiconductor intellectual property core.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] For these customers, Arm Holdings delivers a gate netlist description of the chosen ARM core, along with an abstracted simulation model and test programs to aid design integration and verification.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] More ambitious customers, including integrated device manufacturers (IDM) and foundry operators, choose to acquire the processor IP in synthesizable RTL (Verilog) form.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] With the synthesizable RTL, the customer has the ability to perform architectural level optimisations and extensions.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This allows the designer to achieve exotic design goals not otherwise possible with an unmodified netlist (high clock speed, very low power consumption, instruction set extensions, etc.).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] While Arm Holdings does not grant the licensee the right to resell the ARM architecture itself, licensees may freely sell manufactured products such as chip devices, evaluation boards and complete systems.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Merchant foundries can be a special case; not only are they allowed to sell finished silicon containing ARM cores, they generally hold the right to re-manufacture ARM cores for other customers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm Holdings prices its IP based on perceived value.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Lower performing ARM cores typically have lower licence costs than higher performing cores.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In implementation terms, a synthesisable core costs more than a hard macro (blackbox) core.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Complicating price matters, a merchant foundry that holds an ARM licence, such as Samsung or Fujitsu, can offer fab customers reduced licensing costs.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In exchange for acquiring the ARM core through the foundry's in-house design services, the customer can reduce or eliminate payment of ARM's upfront licence fee.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Compared to dedicated semiconductor foundries (such as TSMC and UMC) without in-house design services, Fujitsu/Samsung charge two- to three-times more per manufactured wafer.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] For low to mid volume applications, a design service foundry offers lower overall pricing (through subsidisation of the licence fee).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] For high volume mass-produced parts, the long term cost reduction achievable through lower wafer pricing reduces the impact of ARM's NRE (non-recurring engineering) costs, making the dedicated foundry a better choice.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In February 2016, ARM announced the Built on ARM Cortex Technology licence, often shortened to Built on Cortex (BoC) licence.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This licence allows companies to partner with ARM and make modifications to ARM Cortex designs.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] These design modifications will not be shared with other companies.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] These semi-custom core designs also have brand freedom, for example Kryo 280.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies that are current licensees of Built on ARM Cortex Technology include Qualcomm.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies can also obtain an ARM *architectural licence* for designing their own CPU cores using the ARM instruction sets.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] These cores must comply fully with the ARM architecture.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Companies that have designed cores that implement an ARM architecture include Apple, AppliedMicro (now: Ampere Computing), Broadcom, Cavium (now: Marvell), Digital Equipment Corporation, Intel, Nvidia, Qualcomm, Samsung Electronics, Fujitsu, and NUVIA Inc.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] On 16 July 2019, ARM announced ARM Flexible Access.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM Flexible Access provides unlimited access to included ARM intellectual property (IP) for development.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Per product licence fees are required once a customer reaches foundry tapeout or prototyping.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] 75% of ARM's most recent IP over the last two years are included in ARM Flexible Access.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARMv3 included a compatibility mode to support the 26-bit addresses of earlier versions of the architecture.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] This compatibility mode is *optional* in ARMv4, and removed entirely in ARMv5.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Arm provides a list of vendors who implement ARM cores in their design (application specific standard products (ASSP), microprocessor and microcontrollers).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM cores are used in a number of products, particularly PDAs and smartphones.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Some computing examples are Microsoft's first generation Surface, Surface 2 and Pocket PC devices (following 2002), Apple's iPads, and Asus's Eee Pad Transformer tablet computers, and several Chromebook laptops.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] Others include Apple's iPhone smartphones and iPod portable media players, Canon PowerShot digital cameras, Nintendo Switch hybrid, the Wii security processor and 3DS handheld game consoles, and TomTom turn-by-turn navigation systems.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] In 2005, Arm took part in the development of Manchester University's computer SpiNNaker, which used ARM cores to simulate the human brain.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p01] ARM chips are also used in Raspberry Pi, BeagleBoard, BeagleBone, PandaBoard, and other single-board computers, because they are very small, inexpensive, and consume very little power.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The 32-bit ARM architecture (**ARM32**), such as **ARMv7-A** (implementing AArch32; see section on Armv8-A for more on it), was the most widely used architecture in mobile devices as of 2011.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Although the architecture profiles were first defined for ARMv7, ARM subsequently defined the ARMv6-M architecture (used by the Cortex M0/M0+/M1) as a subset of the ARMv7-M profile with fewer instructions.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] 26-bit addressing - obsolete as of June 2000.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Multiply and multiply-accumulate instructions; coprocessor support - all variants obsolete as of June 2000.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] 32-bit addressing - all variants obsolete as of July 2005.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] , the former of which supports the 32-bit ARM instruction set, called A32, and the Thumb-2 instruction set, called T32, and the latter of which supports a new instruction set with 32 64-bit registers, called A64.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Except in the M-profile, the 32-bit ARM architecture specifies several CPU modes, depending on the implemented architecture features.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] At any moment in time, the CPU can be in only one mode, but it can switch modes due to external events (interrupts) or programmatically.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The original ARM implementation was hardwired without microcode, like the much simpler 8-bit 6502 processor used in prior Acorn microcomputers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM includes integer arithmetic operations for add, subtract, and multiply; some versions of the architecture also support divide operations.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM supports 32-bit × 32-bit multiplies with either a 32-bit result or 64-bit result, though Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 cores do not support 64-bit results.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some ARM cores also support 16-bit × 16-bit and 32-bit × 16-bit multiplies.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Registers R0 through R7 are the same across all CPU modes; they are never banked.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Registers R8 through R12 are the same across all CPU modes except FIQ mode.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] FIQ mode has its own distinct R8 through R12 registers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] R13 and R14 are banked across all privileged CPU modes except system mode.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] That is, each mode that can be entered because of an exception has its own R13 and R14.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] These registers generally contain the stack pointer and the return address from function calls, respectively.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Current Program Status Register (CPSR) has the following 32 bits.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Almost every ARM instruction has a conditional execution feature called predication, which is implemented with a 4-bit condition code selector (the predicate).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] To allow for unconditional execution, one of the four-bit codes causes the instruction to be always executed.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Most other CPU architectures only have condition codes on branch instructions.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Though the predicate takes up four of the 32 bits in an instruction code, and thus cuts down significantly on the encoding bits available for displacements in memory access instructions, it avoids branch instructions when generating code for small `if` statements.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Apart from eliminating the branch instructions themselves, this preserves the fetch/decode/execute pipeline at the cost of only one cycle per skipped instruction.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] An algorithm that provides a good example of conditional execution is the subtraction-based Euclidean algorithm for computing the greatest common divisor.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] which avoids the branches around the `then` and `else` clauses.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] If `r0` and `r1` are equal then neither of the `SUB` instructions will be executed, eliminating the need for a conditional branch to implement the `while` check at the top of the loop, for example had `SUBLE` (less than or equal) been used.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] One of the ways that Thumb code provides a more dense encoding is to remove the four-bit selector from non-branch instructions.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] This results in the typical ARM program being denser than expected with fewer memory accesses; thus the pipeline is used more efficiently.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM processor also has features rarely seen in other RISC architectures, such as PC-relative addressing (indeed, on the 32-bit ARM the PC is one of its 16 registers) and pre- and post-increment addressing modes.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM instruction set has increased over time.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some early ARM processors (before ARM7TDMI), for example, have no instruction to store a two-byte quantity.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM7 and earlier implementations have a three-stage pipeline; the stages being fetch, decode, and execute.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Higher-performance designs, such as the ARM9, have deeper pipelines: Cortex-A8 has thirteen stages.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Additional implementation changes for higher performance include a faster adder and more extensive branch prediction logic.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The difference between the ARM7DI and ARM7DMI cores, for example, was an improved multiplier; hence the added "M".
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARM architecture (pre-Armv8) provides a non-intrusive way of extending the instruction set using "coprocessors" that can be addressed using MCR, MRC, MRRC, MCRR, and similar instructions.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The coprocessor space is divided logically into 16 coprocessors with numbers from 0 to 15, coprocessor 15 (cp15) being reserved for some typical control functions like managing the caches and MMU operation on processors that have one.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] In ARM-based machines, peripheral devices are usually attached to the processor by mapping their physical registers into ARM memory space, into the coprocessor space, or by connecting to another device (a bus) that in turn attaches to the processor.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Coprocessor accesses have lower latency, so some peripherals—for example, an XScale interrupt controller—are accessible in both ways: through memory and through coprocessors.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] In other cases, chip designers only integrate hardware using the coprocessor mechanism.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, an image processing engine might be a small ARM7TDMI core combined with a coprocessor that has specialised operations to support a specific set of HDTV transcoding primitives.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] All modern ARM processors include hardware debugging facilities, allowing software debuggers to perform operations such as halting, stepping, and breakpointing of code starting from reset.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] These facilities are built using JTAG support, though some newer cores optionally support ARM's own two-wire "SWD" protocol.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] In ARM7TDMI cores, the "D" represented JTAG debug support, and the "I" represented presence of an "EmbeddedICE" debug module.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] For ARM7 and ARM9 core generations, EmbeddedICE over JTAG was a de facto debug standard, though not architecturally guaranteed.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The ARMv7 architecture defines basic debug facilities at an architectural level.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] These include breakpoints, watchpoints and instruction execution in a "Debug Mode"; similar facilities were also available with EmbeddedICE.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Both "halt mode" and "monitor" mode debugging are supported.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The actual transport mechanism used to access the debug facilities is not architecturally specified, but implementations generally include JTAG support.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] There is a separate ARM "CoreSight" debug architecture, which is not architecturally required by ARMv7 processors.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Debug Access Port (DAP) is an implementation of an ARM Debug Interface.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] There are two different supported implementations, the Serial Wire JTAG Debug Port (SWJ-DP) and the Serial Wire Debug Port (SW-DP).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] CMSIS-DAP is a standard interface that describes how various debugging software on a host PC can communicate over USB to firmware running on a hardware debugger, which in turn talks over SWD or JTAG to a CoreSight-enabled ARM Cortex CPU.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] To improve the ARM architecture for digital signal processing and multimedia applications, DSP instructions were added to the instruction set.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] These are signified by an "E" in the name of the ARMv5TE and ARMv5TEJ architectures.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The new instructions are common in digital signal processor (DSP) architectures.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] They include variations on signed multiply–accumulate, saturated add and subtract, and count leading zeros.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] First introduced in 1999, this extension of the core instruction set contrasted with ARM's earlier DSP coprocessor known as Piccolo, which employed a distinct, incompatible instruction set whose execution involved a separate program counter.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Piccolo instructions employed a distinct register file of sixteen 32-bit registers, with some instructions combining registers for use as 48-bit accumulators and other instructions addressing 16-bit half-registers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some instructions were able to operate on two such 16-bit values in parallel.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Communication with the Piccolo register file involved *load to Piccolo* and *store from Piccolo* coprocessor instructions via two buffers of eight 32-bit entries.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Described as reminiscent of other approaches, notably Hitachi's SH-DSP and Motorola's 68356, Piccolo did not employ dedicated local memory and relied on the bandwidth of the ARM core for DSP operand retrieval, impacting concurrent performance.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Piccolo's distinct instruction set also proved not to be a "good compiler target".
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Introduced in the ARMv6 architecture, this was a precursor to Advanced SIMD, also named Neon.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Jazelle DBX (Direct Bytecode eXecution) is a technique that allows Java bytecode to be executed directly in the ARM architecture as a third execution state (and instruction set) alongside the existing ARM and Thumb-mode.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Support for this state is signified by the "J" in the ARMv5TEJ architecture, and in ARM9EJ-S and ARM7EJ-S core names.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Support for this state is required starting in ARMv6 (except for the ARMv7-M profile), though newer cores only include a trivial implementation that provides no hardware acceleration.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] To improve compiled code density, processors since the ARM7TDMI (released in 1994) have featured the *Thumb* compressed instruction set, which have their own state.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] (The "T" in "TDMI" indicates the Thumb feature.) When in this state, the processor executes the Thumb instruction set, a compact 16-bit encoding for a subset of the ARM instruction set.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Most of the Thumb instructions are directly mapped to normal ARM instructions.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The space saving comes from making some of the instruction operands implicit and limiting the number of possibilities compared to the ARM instructions executed in the ARM instruction set state.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Thumb, the 16-bit opcodes have less functionality.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, only branches can be conditional, and many opcodes are restricted to accessing only half of all of the CPU's general-purpose registers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The shorter opcodes give improved code density overall, even though some operations require extra instructions.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] In situations where the memory port or bus width is constrained to less than 32 bits, the shorter Thumb opcodes allow increased performance compared with 32-bit ARM code, as less program code may need to be loaded into the processor over the constrained memory bandwidth.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Unlike processor architectures with variable length (16- or 32-bit) instructions, such as the Cray-1 and Hitachi SuperH, the ARM and Thumb instruction sets exist independently of each other.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Embedded hardware, such as the Game Boy Advance, typically have a small amount of RAM accessible with a full 32-bit datapath; the majority is accessed via a 16-bit or narrower secondary datapath.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] In this situation, it usually makes sense to compile Thumb code and hand-optimise a few of the most CPU-intensive sections using full 32-bit ARM instructions, placing these wider instructions into the 32-bit bus accessible memory.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first processor with a Thumb instruction decoder was the ARM7TDMI.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] All processors supporting 32-bit instruction sets, starting with ARM9, and including XScale, have included a Thumb instruction decoder.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] It includes instructions adopted from the Hitachi SuperH (1992), which was licensed by ARM.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM's smallest processor families (Cortex M0 and M1) implement only the 16-bit Thumb instruction set for maximum performance in lowest cost applications.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM processors that don't support 32-bit addressing also omit Thumb.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Thumb-2 extends the Thumb instruction set with bit-field manipulation, table branches and conditional execution.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] At the same time, the ARM instruction set was extended to maintain equivalent functionality in both instruction sets.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] A new "Unified Assembly Language" (UAL) supports generation of either Thumb or ARM instructions from the same source code; versions of Thumb seen on ARMv7 processors are essentially as capable as ARM code (including the ability to write interrupt handlers).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] This requires a bit of care, and use of a new "IT" (if-then) instruction, which permits up to four successive instructions to execute based on a tested condition, or on its inverse.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] When compiling into ARM code, this is ignored, but when compiling into Thumb it generates an actual instruction.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] All ARMv7 chips support the Thumb instruction set.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] All chips in the Cortex-A series that support ARMv7, all Cortex-R series, and all ARM11 series support both "ARM instruction set state" and "Thumb instruction set state", while chips in the Cortex-M series support only the Thumb instruction set.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] New features provided by ThumbEE include automatic null pointer checks on every load and store instruction, an instruction to perform an array bounds check, and special instructions that call a handler.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] In addition, because it utilises Thumb-2 technology, ThumbEE provides access to registers r8–r15 (where the Jazelle/DBX Java VM state is held).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Handlers are small sections of frequently called code, commonly used to implement high level languages, such as allocating memory for a new object.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] These changes come from repurposing a handful of opcodes, and knowing the core is in the new ThumbEE state.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] On 23 November 2011, Arm deprecated any use of the ThumbEE instruction set, and Armv8 removes support for ThumbEE.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some devices such as the ARM Cortex-A8 have a cut-down *VFPLite* module instead of a full VFP module, and require roughly ten times more clock cycles per float operation.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Pre-Armv8 architecture implemented floating-point/SIMD with the coprocessor interface.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Other floating-point and/or SIMD units found in ARM-based processors using the coprocessor interface include FPA, FPE, iwMMXt, some of which were implemented in software by trapping but could have been implemented in hardware.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] They provide some of the same functionality as VFP but are not opcode-compatible with it.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] FPA10 also provides extended precision, but implements correct rounding (required by IEEE 754) only in single precision.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] An optional extension to the ARM instruction set in the ARMv5TE, ARMv5TEJ and ARMv6 architectures.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on most Cortex-A8 and A9 ARMv7 processors.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] It is backward-compatible with VFPv2, except that it cannot trap floating-point exceptions.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] VFPv3 has 32 64-bit FPU registers as standard, adds VCVT instructions to convert between scalar, float and double, adds immediate mode to VMOV such that constants can be loaded into FPU registers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] As above, but with only 16 64-bit FPU registers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-A12 and A15 ARMv7 processors, Cortex-A7 optionally has VFPv4-D32 in the case of an FPU with Neon.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] As above, but it has only 16 64-bit FPU registers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-A5 and A7 processors in the case of an FPU without Neon.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Implemented on Cortex-M7 when single and double-precision floating-point core option exists.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Debian Linux and derivatives such as Ubuntu and Linux Mint, **armhf** (**ARM hard float**) refers to the ARMv7 architecture including the additional VFP3-D16 floating-point hardware extension (and Thumb-2) above.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Software packages and cross-compiler tools use the armhf vs. arm/armel suffixes to differentiate.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The *Advanced SIMD* extension (also known as *Neon* or "MPE" Media Processing Engine) is a combined 64- and 128-bit SIMD instruction set that provides standardised acceleration for media and signal processing applications.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon is included in all Cortex-A8 devices, but is optional in Cortex-A9 devices.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon can execute MP3 audio decoding on CPUs running at 10 MHz, and can run the GSM adaptive multi-rate (AMR) speech codec at 13 MHz.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] It features a comprehensive instruction set, separate register files, and independent execution hardware.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Neon supports 8-, 16-, 32-, and 64-bit integer and single-precision (32-bit) floating-point data and SIMD operations for handling audio and video processing as well as graphics and gaming processing.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] In Neon, the SIMD supports up to 16 operations at the same time.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Neon hardware shares the same floating-point registers as used in VFP.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Devices such as the ARM Cortex-A8 and Cortex-A9 support 128-bit vectors, but will execute with 64 bits at a time, whereas some more powerful CPUs such as Cortex-A15 can execute 128 bits at a time.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] A quirk of Neon in Armv7 devices is that it flushes all subnormal numbers to zero, and as a result the GCC compiler will not use it unless `-funsafe-math-optimizations`, which allows losing denormals, is turned on.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] "Enhanced" Neon defined since Armv8 does not have this quirk, but as of GCC 8.2 the same flag is still required to enable Neon instructions.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] On the other hand, GCC does consider Neon safe on AArch64 for Armv8.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] ProjectNe10 is ARM's first open-source project (from its inception; while they acquired an older project, now named Mbed TLS).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Ne10 library is a set of common, useful functions written in both Neon and C (for compatibility).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The library was created to allow developers to use Neon optimisations without learning Neon, but it also serves as a set of highly optimised Neon intrinsic and assembly code examples for common DSP, arithmetic, and image processing routines.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Helium is the M-Profile Vector Extension (MVE).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] It adds more than 150 scalar and vector instructions.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Security Extensions, marketed as TrustZone Technology, is in ARMv6KZ and later application profile architectures.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] It provides a low-cost alternative to adding another dedicated security core to an SoC, by providing two virtual processors backed by hardware based access control.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] This lets the application core switch between two states, referred to as *worlds* (to reduce confusion with other names for capability domains), to prevent information leaking from the more trusted world (the *Secure world*) to the less trusted world (the *Normal world*).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] This world switch is generally orthogonal to all other capabilities of the processor, thus each world can operate independently of the other while using the same core.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Memory and peripherals are then made aware of the operating world of the core and may use this to provide access control to secrets and code on the device.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Typically, a rich operating system is run in the less trusted world, with smaller security-specialised code in the more trusted world, aiming to reduce the attack surface.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Typical applications include DRM functionality for controlling the use of media on ARM-based devices, and preventing any unapproved use of the device.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] In practice, since the specific implementation details of proprietary TrustZone implementations have not been publicly disclosed for review, it is unclear what level of assurance is provided for a given threat model, but they are not immune from attack.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Open Virtualization is an open source implementation of the trusted world architecture for TrustZone.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] AMD has licensed and incorporated TrustZone technology into its Secure Processor Technology.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] AMD's APUs include a Cortex-A5 processor for handling secure processing, which is enabled in some, but not all products.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] In fact, the Cortex-A5 TrustZone core had been included in earlier AMD products, but was not enabled due to time constraints.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Samsung Knox uses TrustZone for purposes such as detecting modifications to the kernel, storing certificates and attestating keys.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Security Extension, marketed as TrustZone for Armv8-M Technology, was introduced in the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] While containing similar concepts to TrustZone for Armv8-A, it has a different architectural design, as world switching is performed using branch instructions instead of using exceptions.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also supports safe interleaved interrupt handling from either world regardless of the current security state.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Together these features provide low latency calls to the secure world and responsive interrupt handling.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM provides a reference stack of secure world code in the form of Trusted Firmware for M and PSA Certified.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] As of ARMv6, the ARM architecture supports no-execute page protection, which is referred to as *XN*, for *eXecute Never*.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Large Physical Address Extension (LPAE), which extends the physical address size from 32 bits to 40 bits, was added to the Armv7-A architecture in 2011.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The physical address size may be even larger in processors based on the 64-bit (Armv8-A) architecture.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, it is 44 bits in Cortex-A75 and Cortex-A65AE.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The **Armv8-R** and **Armv8-M** architectures, announced after the Armv8-A architecture, share some features with Armv8-A.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] However, Armv8-M does not include any 64-bit AArch64 instructions, and Armv8-R originally did not include any AArch64 instructions; those instructions were added to Armv8-R later.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Armv8.1-M architecture, announced in February 2019, is an enhancement of the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Announced in October 2011, **Armv8-A** (often called ARMv8 while the Armv8-R is also available) represents a fundamental change to the ARM architecture.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] It supports two *Execution states*: a 64-bit state named *AArch64* and a 32-bit state named *AArch32*.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] In the AArch64 state, a new 64-bit *A64* instruction set is supported; in the AArch32 state, two instruction sets are supported: the original 32-bit instruction set, named *A32*, and the 32-bit Thumb-2 instruction set, named *T32*.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch32 provides user-space compatibility with Armv7-A.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The processor state can change on an Exception level change; this allows 32-bit applications to be executed in AArch32 state under a 64-bit OS whose kernel executes in AArch64 state, and allows a 32-bit OS to run in AArch32 state under the control of a 64-bit hypervisor running in AArch64 state.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] ARM announced their Cortex-A53 and Cortex-A57 cores on 30 October 2012.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Apple was the first to release an Armv8-A compatible core in a consumer product (Apple A7 in iPhone 5S).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] AppliedMicro, using an FPGA, was the first to demo Armv8-A.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first Armv8-A SoC from Samsung is the Exynos 5433 used in the Galaxy Note 4, which features two clusters of four Cortex-A57 and Cortex-A53 cores in a big.LITTLE configuration; but it will run only in AArch32 mode.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] To both AArch32 and AArch64, Armv8-A makes VFPv3/v4 and advanced SIMD (Neon) standard.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also adds cryptography instructions supporting AES, SHA-1/SHA-256 and finite field arithmetic.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch64 was introduced in Armv8-A and its subsequent revision.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] AArch64 is not included in the 32-bit Armv8-R and Armv8-M architectures.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] An ARMv8-A processor can support one or both of AArch32 and AArch64; it may support AArch32 and AArch64 at lower Exception levels and only AArch64 at higher Exception levels.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] For example, the ARM Cortex-A32 supports only AArch32, the ARM Cortex-A34 supports only AArch64, and the ARM Cortex-A72 supports both AArch64 and AArch32.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] An ARMv9-A processor must support AArch64 at all Exception levels, and may support AArch32 at EL0.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Optional AArch64 support was added to the Armv8-R profile, with the first ARM core implementing it being the Cortex-R82.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Announced in March 2021, the updated architecture places a focus on secure execution and compartmentalisation.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first ARMv9-A processors were released later that year, including the Cortex-A510, Cortex-A710 and Cortex-X2.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Arm SystemReady is a compliance program that helps ensure the interoperability of an operating system on Arm-based hardware from datacenter servers to industrial edge and IoT devices.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The key building blocks of the program are the specifications for minimum hardware and firmware requirements that the operating systems and hypervisors can rely upon.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] These specifications are co-developed by Arm and its partners in the System Architecture Advisory Committee (SystemArchAC).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Architecture Compliance Suite (ACS) is the test tools that help to check the compliance of these specifications.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Arm SystemReady Requirements Specification documents the requirements of the certifications.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] This program was introduced by Arm in 2020 at the first DevSummit event.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Its predecessor Arm ServerReady was introduced in 2018 at the Arm TechCon event.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified, formerly named Platform Security Architecture, is an architecture-agnostic security framework and evaluation scheme.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] It is intended to help secure Internet of things (IoT) devices built on system-on-a-chip (SoC) processors.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] It was introduced to increase security where a full trusted execution environment is too large or complex.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The architecture was introduced by Arm in 2017 at the annual TechCon event.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Although the scheme is architecture agnostic, it was first implemented on Arm Cortex-M processor cores intended for microcontroller use.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified includes freely available threat models and security analyses that demonstrate the process for deciding on security features in common IoT products.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] It also provides freely downloadable application programming interface (API) packages, architectural specifications, open-source firmware implementations, and related test suites.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Following the development of the architecture security framework in 2017, the PSA Certified assurance scheme launched two years later at Embedded World in 2019.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified offers a multi-level security evaluation scheme for chip vendors, OS providers and IoT device makers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The Embedded World presentation introduced chip vendors to Level 1 Certification.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] A draft of Level 2 protection was presented at the same time.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Level 2 certification became a usable standard in February 2020.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The certification was created by PSA Joint Stakeholders to enable a security-by-design approach for a diverse set of IoT products.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] PSA Certified specifications are implementation and architecture agnostic, as a result they can be applied to any chip, software or device.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The certification also removes industry fragmentation for IoT product manufacturers and developers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The first 32-bit ARM-based personal computer, the Acorn Archimedes, was originally intended to run an ambitious operating system called ARX.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] The machines shipped with RISC OS, which was also used on later ARM-based systems from Acorn and other vendors.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/arm-architecture-family-p02] Some early Acorn machines were also able to run a Unix port called RISC iX.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Dangling pointers arise during object destruction, when an object that is pointed to by a given pointer is deleted or deallocated, without modifying the value of that said pointer, so that the pointer still points to the memory location of the deallocated memory.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] The system may reallocate the previously freed memory, and if the program then dereferences the (now) dangling pointer, *unpredictable behavior may result*, as the memory may now contain completely different data.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] If the program writes to memory referenced by a dangling pointer, a silent corruption of unrelated data may result, leading to subtle bugs that can be extremely difficult to find.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] If the memory has been reallocated to another process, then attempting to dereference the dangling pointer can cause segmentation faults (UNIX, Linux) or general protection faults (Windows).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] If the program has sufficient privileges to allow it to overwrite the bookkeeping data used by the kernel's memory allocator, the corruption can cause system instabilities.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] In object-oriented languages with garbage collection, dangling references are prevented by only destroying objects that are unreachable, meaning they do not have any incoming pointers; this is ensured either by tracing or reference counting.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] However, a finalizer may create new references to an object, requiring object resurrection to prevent a dangling reference.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Wild pointers, also called uninitialized pointers, arise when a pointer is used prior to initialization to some known state, which is possible in some programming languages.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] They show the same erratic behavior as dangling pointers, though they are less likely to stay undetected because many compilers will raise a warning at compile time if declared variables are accessed before being initialized.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] In many languages (e.g., the C programming language) deleting an object from memory explicitly or by destroying the stack frame on return does not alter associated pointers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] The pointer still points to the same location in memory even though that location may now be used for other purposes.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] If the operating system is able to detect run-time references to null pointers, a solution to the above is to assign 0 (null) to dp immediately before the inner block is exited.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Another solution would be to somehow guarantee dp is not used again without further initialization.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Another frequent source of dangling pointers is a jumbled combination of `malloc()` and `free()` library calls: a pointer becomes dangling when the block of memory it points to is freed.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] As with the previous example one way to avoid this is to make sure to reset the pointer to null after freeing its reference—as demonstrated below.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] An all too common misstep is returning addresses of a stack-allocated local variable: once a called function returns, the space for these variables gets deallocated and technically they have "garbage values".
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Attempts to read from the pointer may still return the correct value (1234) for a while after calling `func`, but any functions called thereafter may overwrite the stack storage allocated for `num` with other values and the pointer would no longer work correctly.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] If a pointer to `num` must be returned, `num` must have scope beyond the function—it might be declared as `static`.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Antoni Kreczmar (1945–1996) has created a complete object management system which is free of dangling reference phenomenon.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] A similar approach was proposed by Fisher and LeBlanc under the name *Locks-and-keys*.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Wild pointers are created by omitting necessary initialization prior to first use.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Thus, strictly speaking, every pointer in programming languages which do not enforce initialization begins as a wild pointer.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] This most often occurs due to jumping over the initialization, not by omitting it.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Most compilers are able to warn about this.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Like buffer-overflow bugs, dangling/wild pointer bugs frequently become security holes.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] For example, if the pointer is used to make a virtual function call, a different address (possibly pointing at exploit code) may be called due to the vtable pointer being overwritten.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Alternatively, if the pointer is used for writing to memory, some other data structure may be corrupted.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Even if the memory is only read once the pointer becomes dangling, it can lead to information leaks (if interesting data is put in the next structure allocated there) or to privilege escalation (if the now-invalid memory is used in security checks).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] When a dangling pointer is used after it has been freed without allocating a new chunk of memory to it, this becomes known as a "use after free" vulnerability.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] For example, CVE-2014-1776 is a use-after-free vulnerability in Microsoft Internet Explorer 6 through 11 that was used by zero-day attacks by an advanced persistent threat.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] In C, the simplest technique is to implement an alternative version of the `free()` (or alike) function which guarantees the reset of the pointer.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] However, this technique will not clear other pointer variables which may contain a copy of the pointer.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] These uses can be masked through `#define` directives to construct useful macros (a common one being `#define XFREE(ptr) safeFree((void**)&(ptr))`), creating something like a metalanguage or can be embedded into a tool library apart.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] In every case, programmers using this technique should use the safe versions in every instance where `free()` would be used; failing in doing so leads again to the problem.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Also, this solution is limited to the scope of a single program or project, and should be properly documented.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Among more structured solutions, a popular technique to avoid dangling pointers in C++ is to use smart pointers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] A smart pointer typically uses reference counting to reclaim objects.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Some other techniques include the tombstones method and the locks-and-keys method.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Another approach is to use the Boehm garbage collector, a conservative garbage collector that replaces standard memory allocation functions in C and C++ with a garbage collector.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] This approach completely eliminates dangling pointer errors by disabling frees, and reclaiming objects by garbage collection.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Another approach is to use a system such as CHERI, which stores pointers with additional metadata which may prevent invalid accesses by including lifetime information in pointers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] CHERI typically requires support in the CPU to conduct these additional checks.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] In languages like Java, dangling pointers cannot occur because there is no mechanism to explicitly deallocate memory.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Rather, the garbage collector may deallocate memory, but only when the object is no longer reachable from any references.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] In the language Rust, the type system has been extended to include also the variables lifetimes and resource acquisition is initialization.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Unless one disables the features of the language, dangling pointers will be caught at compile time and reported as programming errors.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] To expose dangling pointer errors, one common programming technique is to set pointers to the null pointer or to an invalid address once the storage they point to has been released.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] When the null pointer is dereferenced (in most languages) the program will immediately terminate—there is no potential for data corruption or unpredictable behavior.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] This makes the underlying programming mistake easier to find and resolve.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] This technique does not help when there are multiple copies of the pointer.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Some debuggers will automatically overwrite and destroy data that has been freed, usually with a specific pattern, such as `0xDEADBEEF` (Microsoft's Visual C/C++ debugger, for example, uses `0xCC`, `0xCD` or `0xDD` depending on what has been freed).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] This usually prevents the data from being reused by making it useless and also very prominent (the pattern serves to show the programmer that the memory has already been freed).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Tools such as Polyspace, TotalView, Valgrind, Mudflap, AddressSanitizer, or tools based on LLVM can also be used to detect uses of dangling pointers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] Other tools (SoftBound, Insure++, and CheckPointer) instrument the source code to collect and track legitimate values for pointers ("metadata") and check each pointer access against the metadata for validity.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/dangling-pointer] The ARM64 memory tagging extension (MTE) - disabled by default on Linux systems, but can be enabled on Android 16 - triggers a segmentation fault when it detects use-after-free and buffer overflow.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Segmentation refers to dividing a computer's memory into segments.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] A reference to a memory location includes a value that identifies a segment and an offset within that segment.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] A segment descriptor may limit access rights, e.g., read only, only from certain rings.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] The x86 architecture has multiple segmentation features, which are helpful for using protected memory on this architecture.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] On the x86 architecture, the Global Descriptor Table and Local Descriptor Tables can be used to reference segments in the computer's memory.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Pointers to memory segments on x86 processors can also be stored in the processor's segment registers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Initially x86 processors had 4 segment registers, CS (code segment), SS (stack segment), DS (data segment) and ES (extra segment); later another two segment registers were added – FS and GS.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] In paging the memory address space or segment is divided into equal-sized blocks called pages.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Using virtual memory hardware, each page can reside in any location at a suitable boundary of the computer's physical memory, or be flagged as being protected.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Virtual memory makes it possible to have a linear virtual memory address space and to use it to access blocks fragmented over physical memory address space.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Most computer architectures which support paging also use pages as the basis for memory protection.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] A *page table* maps virtual memory to physical memory.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] There may be a single page table, a page table for each process, a page table for each segment, or a hierarchy of page tables, depending on the architecture and the OS.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] The page tables are usually invisible to the process.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Page tables make it easier to allocate additional memory, as each new page can be allocated from anywhere in physical memory.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] On some systems a page table entry can also designate a page as read-only.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Some operating systems set up a different address space for each process, which provides hard memory protection boundaries.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] It is impossible for an unprivileged application to access a page that has not been explicitly allocated to it, because every memory address either points to a page allocated to that application, or generates an interrupt called a *page fault*.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Unallocated pages, and pages allocated to any other application, do not have any addresses from the application point of view.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] A page fault may not necessarily indicate an error.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Page faults are not only used for memory protection.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] The operating system may manage the page table in such a way that a reference to a page that has been previously paged out to secondary storage causes a page fault.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] The operating system intercepts the page fault, loads the required memory page, and the application continues as if no fault had occurred.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] This scheme, a type of virtual memory, allows in-memory data not currently in use to be moved to secondary storage and back in a way which is transparent to applications, to increase overall memory capacity.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] On some systems, a request for virtual storage may allocate a block of virtual addresses for which no page frames have been assigned, and the system will only assign and initialize page frames when page faults occur.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] On some systems a guard page may be used, either for error detection or to automatically grow data structures.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] On some systems, the page fault mechanism is also used for executable-space protection such as W^X.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] A memory protection key (MPK) mechanism divides physical memory into blocks of a particular size (e.g., 4 KiB), each of which has an associated numerical value called a protection key.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Each process also has a protection key value associated with it.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] On a memory access the hardware checks that the current process's protection key matches the value associated with the memory block being accessed; if not, an exception occurs.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] This mechanism was introduced in the System/360 architecture.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] It is available on today's System z mainframes and heavily used by System z operating systems and their subsystems.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] The System/360 protection keys described above are associated with physical addresses.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] This is different from the protection key mechanism used by architectures such as the Hewlett-Packard/Intel IA-64 and Hewlett-Packard PA-RISC, which are associated with virtual addresses, and which allow multiple keys per process.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] In the Itanium and PA-RISC architectures, translations (TLB entries) have *keys* (Itanium) or *access ids* (PA-RISC) associated with them.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] A running process has several protection key registers (16 for Itanium, 4 for PA-RISC).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] A translation selected by the virtual address has its key compared to each of the protection key registers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] If any of them match (plus other possible checks), the access is permitted.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] If none match, a fault or exception is generated.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] The software fault handler can, if desired, check the missing key against a larger list of keys maintained by software; thus, the protection key registers inside the processor may be treated as a software-managed cache of a larger list of keys associated with a process.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] PA-RISC has 15–18 bits of key; Itanium mandates at least 18.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Keys are usually associated with *protection domains*, such as libraries, modules, etc.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] In the x86, the protection keys architecture allows tagging virtual addresses for user pages with any of 16 protection keys.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] All the pages tagged with the same protection key constitute a protection domain.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] A new register contains the permissions associated with each of the protection domain.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Load and store operations are checked against both the page table permissions and the protection key permissions associated with the protection domain of the virtual address, and only allowed if both permissions allow the access.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] The protection key permissions can be set from user space, allowing applications to directly restrict access to the application data without OS intervention.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Since the protection keys are associated with a virtual address, the protection domains are per address space, so processes running in different address spaces can each use all 16 domains.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] In Multics and systems derived from it, each segment has a protection ring for reading, writing and execution; an attempt by a process with a higher ring number than the ring number for the segment causes a fault.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] There is a mechanism for safely calling procedures that run in a lower ring and returning to the higher ring.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] There are mechanisms for a routine running with a low ring number to access a parameter with the larger of its own ring and the caller's ring.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Simulation is the use of a monitoring program to interpret the machine code instructions of some computer architectures.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Such an instruction set simulator can provide memory protection by using a segmentation-like scheme and validating the target address and length of each instruction in real time before actually executing them.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] The simulator must calculate the target address and length and compare this against a list of valid address ranges that it holds concerning the thread's environment, such as any dynamic memory blocks acquired since the thread's inception, plus any valid shared static memory slots.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] The meaning of "valid" may change throughout the thread's life depending upon context.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] It may sometimes be allowed to alter a static block of storage, and sometimes not, depending upon the current mode of execution, which may or may not depend on a storage key or supervisor state.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] It is generally not advisable to use this method of memory protection where adequate facilities exist on a CPU, as this takes valuable processing power from the computer.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Capability-based addressing is a method of memory protection that is unused in modern commercial computers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] In this method, pointers are replaced by protected objects (called *capabilities*) that can only be created using privileged instructions which may only be executed by the kernel, or some other process authorized to do so.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] This effectively lets the kernel control which processes may access which objects in memory, with no need to use separate address spaces or context switches.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Only a few commercial products used capability based security: Plessey System 250, IBM System/38, Intel iAPX 432 architecture and KeyKOS.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Capability approaches are widely used in research systems such as EROS and Combex DARPA browser.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] They are used conceptually as the basis for some virtual machines, most notably Smalltalk and Java.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Currently, the DARPA-funded CHERI project at University of Cambridge is working to create a modern capability machine that also supports legacy software.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Dynamic tainting is a technique for protecting programs from illegal memory accesses.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] When memory is allocated, at runtime, this technique taints both the memory and the corresponding pointer using the same taint mark.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Taint marks are then suitably propagated while the program executes and are checked every time a memory address *m* is accessed through a pointer *p*; if the taint marks associated with *m* and *p* differ, the execution is stopped and the illegal access is reported.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] SPARC M7 processors (and higher) implement dynamic tainting in hardware.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Oracle markets this feature as Silicon Secured Memory (SSM) (previously branded as Application Data Integrity (ADI)).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] The lowRISC CPU design includes dynamic tainting under the name Tagged Memory.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] The protection level of a particular implementation may be measured by how closely it adheres to the principle of minimum privilege.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Different operating systems use different forms of memory protection or separation.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] Although memory protection was common on most mainframes and many minicomputer systems from the 1960s, true memory separation was not used in home computer operating systems until OS/2 (and in RISC OS) was released in 1987.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] On prior systems, such lack of protection was even used as a form of interprocess communication, by sending a pointer between processes.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] It is possible for processes to access System Memory in the Windows 9x family of operating systems.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-protection] On Unix-like systems, the `mprotect` system call is used to control memory protection.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] Memory errors were first considered in the context of resource management (computing) and time-sharing systems, in an effort to avoid problems such as fork bombs.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] Developments were mostly theoretical until the Morris worm, which exploited a buffer overflow in fingerd.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] The field of computer security developed quickly thereafter, escalating with multitudes of new attacks such as the return-to-libc attack and defense techniques such as the non-executable stack and address space layout randomization.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] Randomization prevents most buffer overflow attacks and requires the attacker to use heap spraying or other application-dependent methods to obtain addresses, although its adoption has been slow.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] However, deployments of the technology are typically limited to randomizing libraries and the location of the stack.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] In 2019, a Microsoft security engineer reported that 70% of all security vulnerabilities were caused by memory safety issues.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] In 2020, a team at Google similarly reported that 70% of all "severe security bugs" in Chromium were caused by memory safety problems.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] Many other high-profile vulnerabilities and exploits in critical software have ultimately stemmed from a lack of memory safety, including Heartbleed and a long-standing privilege escalation bug in sudo.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] The pervasiveness and severity of vulnerabilities and exploits arising from memory safety issues have led several security researchers to describe identifying memory safety issues as "shooting fish in a barrel".
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] Some modern high-level programming languages are memory-safe by default, though not completely since they only check their own code and not the system they interact with.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] Automatic memory management in the form of garbage collection is the most common technique for preventing some of the memory safety problems, since it prevents common memory safety errors like use-after-free for all data allocated within the language runtime.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] However, the performance overhead of garbage collection makes these languages unsuitable for certain performance-critical applications.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] For languages that use manual memory management, memory safety is not usually guaranteed by the runtime.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] Instead, memory safety properties must either be guaranteed by the compiler via static program analysis and automated theorem proving or carefully managed by the programmer at runtime.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] For example, the Rust programming language implements a borrow checker to ensure memory safety, while C and C++ provide no memory safety guarantees.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] The substantial amount of software written in C and C++ has motivated the development of external static analysis tools like Coverity, which offers static memory analysis for C.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] DieHard, its redesign DieHarder, and the Allinea Distributed Debugging Tool are special heap allocators that allocate objects in their own random virtual memory page, allowing invalid reads and writes to be stopped and debugged at the exact instruction that causes them.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] Protection relies upon hardware memory protection and thus overhead is typically not substantial, although it can grow significantly if the program makes heavy use of allocation.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] Randomization provides only probabilistic protection against memory errors, but can often be easily implemented in existing software by relinking the binary.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] The memcheck tool of Valgrind uses an instruction set simulator and runs the compiled program in a memory-checking virtual machine, providing guaranteed detection of a subset of runtime memory errors.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] However, it typically slows the program down by a factor of 40, and furthermore must be explicitly informed of custom memory allocators.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] With access to the source code, libraries exist that collect and track legitimate values for pointers ("metadata") and check each pointer access against the metadata for validity, such as the Boehm garbage collector.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] In general, memory safety can be safely assured using tracing garbage collection and the insertion of runtime checks on every memory access; this approach has overhead, but less than that of Valgrind.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] All garbage-collected languages take this approach.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] For C and C++, many tools exist that perform a compile-time transformation of the code to do memory safety checks at runtime, such as CheckPointer and AddressSanitizer which imposes an average slowdown factor of 2.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] BoundWarden is a new spatial memory enforcement approach that utilizes a combination of compile-time transformation and runtime concurrent monitoring techniques.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] Fuzz testing is well-suited for finding memory safety bugs and is often used in combination with dynamic checkers such as AddressSanitizer.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] Some lists may also include **race conditions** (concurrent reads/writes to shared memory) as being part of memory safety (e.g., for access control).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] The Rust programming language prevents many kinds of memory-based race conditions by default, because it ensures there is at most one writer *or* one or more readers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] Many other programming languages, such as Java, do *not* automatically prevent memory-based race conditions, yet are still generally considered "memory safe" languages.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/memory-safety] Therefore, countering race conditions is generally *not* considered necessary for a language to be considered memory safe.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] Some early systems use tagging of data in memory but do not have all of the characteristics now considered to be part of tagged architectures.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] The RCA 601 has a 3-bit tag register and a 3-bit tag for every 24-bit half-word.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] Every instruction can request a test for equal or unequal tag, and cause a maskable interrupt if the specified match fails.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] There is no architectural connection between the tag and the contents of the half-word; it is strictly determined by the software.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] The Burroughs B5000, B5500 and B5700 have 48-bit words with no appended tag field.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] However, while there are no tag fields for character, instruction or numeric (floating point) words, all of the control word formats include a 3-bit tag.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] The Burroughs B6500 and its successors have a 3-bit tag for every word.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] In contrast, program and data memory are indistinguishable in the von Neumann architecture, making the way the memory is referenced critical to interpret the correct meaning.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] Notable examples of American tagged architectures were the Lisp machines, which had tagged pointer support at the hardware and opcode level, the Burroughs B6500 and successors, which have a data-driven tagged and descriptor-based architecture, and the non-commercial Rice Computer.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] Both the Burroughs and Lisp machine are examples of high-level language computer architectures, where the tagging is used to support types from a high-level language at the hardware level.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] In addition to this, the original Xerox Smalltalk implementation used the least-significant bit of each 16-bit word as a tag bit: if it was clear then the hardware would accept it as an aligned memory address while if it was set it was treated as a (shifted) 15-bit integer.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] Current Intel documentation mentions that the lower bits of a memory address might be similarly used by some interpreter-based systems.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] In the Soviet Union, the Elbrus series of supercomputers pioneered the use of tagged architectures in 1973.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] The RISC-V J extension and memory-tagging extension (Zimt) both propose adding some support for tagged architecture at the instruction level.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-architecture] CHERI (Capability Hardware Enhanced RISC Instructions) uses a tagged architecture to add capability-based addressing to several existing ISAs such as x86, MIPS, and RISC-V.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] In computer science, a **tagged pointer** is a pointer (concretely a memory address) with additional data associated with it, such as an indirection bit or reference count.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] This additional data is often "folded" into the pointer, meaning stored inline in the data representing the address, taking advantage of certain properties of memory addressing.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] There are various techniques for folding tags into a pointer.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] Most architectures are byte-addressable (the smallest addressable unit is a byte), but certain types of data will often be *aligned* to the size of the data, often a word or multiple thereof.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] This discrepancy leaves a few of the least significant bits of the pointer unused, which can be used for tags – most often as a bit field (each bit a separate tag) – as long as code that uses the pointer masks out these bits before accessing memory.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] In cases where data is aligned at a multiple of word size, further bits are available.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] In case of word-addressable architectures, word-aligned data does not leave any bits available, as there is no discrepancy between alignment and addressing, but data aligned at a multiple of word size does.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] Conversely, in some operating systems, virtual addresses are narrower than the overall architecture width, which leaves the most significant bits available for tags; this can be combined with the previous technique in case of aligned addresses.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] This is particularly the case on 64-bit architectures, as 64 bits of address space are far above the data requirements of all but the largest applications, and thus many practical 64-bit processors have narrower addresses.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] In fact, some processors specifically forbid use of such tagged pointers at the processor level, notably x86-64, which requires the use of canonical form addresses by the operating system, with most significant bits all 0s or all 1s.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] Lastly, the virtual memory system in most modern operating systems reserves a block of logical memory around address 0 as unusable.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] This means that, for example, a pointer to 0 is never a valid pointer and can be used as a special null pointer value.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] Unlike the previously mentioned techniques, this only allows a single special pointer value, not extra data for pointers generally.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] One of the earliest examples of hardware support for tagged pointers in a commercial platform was the IBM System/38.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] IBM later added tagged pointer support to the PowerPC architecture to support the IBM i operating system, which is an evolution of the System/38 platform.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] A significant example of the use of tagged pointers is the Objective-C runtime on iOS 7 on ARM64, notably used on the iPhone 5S.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] In iOS 7, virtual addresses only contain 33 bits of address information but are 64-bits long leaving 31 bits for tags.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] Objective-C class pointers are 8-byte aligned freeing up an additional 3 bits of address space, and the tag fields are used for many purposes, such as storing a reference count and whether the object has a destructor.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] Early versions of macOS used tagged addresses called Handles to store references to data objects.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] The high bits of the address indicated whether the data object was locked, purgeable, and/or originated from a resource file, respectively.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] This caused compatibility problems, when macOS addressing advanced from 24 bits to 32 bits in System 7.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] Use of zero to represent a null pointer is extremely common, with many programming languages (such as Ada) explicitly relying on this behavior.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] In theory, other values in an operating system-reserved block of logical memory could be used to tag conditions other than a null pointer, but these uses appear to be rare, perhaps because they are at best non-portable.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] It is generally accepted practice in software design that if a special pointer value distinct from null (such as a sentinel in certain data structures) is needed, the programmer should explicitly provide for it.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] Taking advantage of the alignment of pointers provides more flexibility than null pointers/sentinels because it allows pointers to be tagged with information about the type of data pointed to, conditions under which it may be accessed, or other similar information about the pointer's use.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] This information can be provided along with every valid pointer.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] In contrast, null pointers/sentinels provide only a finite number of tagged values distinct from valid pointers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] In a tagged architecture, a number of bits in every word of memory are reserved to act as a tag.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] Tagged architectures, such as the Lisp machines, often have hardware support for interpreting and processing tagged pointers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] GNU libc `malloc()` provides 8-byte aligned memory addresses for 32-bit platforms, and 16-byte alignment for 64-bit platforms.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] Larger alignment values can be obtained with `posix_memalign()`.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] Assume we have a data structure `table_entry` that is always aligned to a 16 byte boundary.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] In other words, the least significant 4 bits of a table entry's address are always 0 (24 = 16).
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] We could use these 4 bits to mark the table entry with extra information.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] For example, bit 0 might mean read only, bit 1 might mean dirty (the table entry needs to be updated), and so on.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] The major advantage of tagged pointers is that they take up less space than a pointer along with a separate tag field.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] This can be especially important when a pointer is a return value from a function.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] It can also be important in large tables of pointers.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] A more subtle advantage is that by storing a tag in the same place as the pointer, it is often possible to guarantee the atomicity of an operation that updates both the pointer and its tag without external synchronization mechanisms.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] This can be an extremely large performance gain, especially in operating systems.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] Tagged pointers have some of the same difficulties as xor linked lists, although to a lesser extent.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] For example, not all debuggers will be able to properly follow tagged pointers; however, this is not an issue for a debugger that is designed with tagged pointers in mind.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] The use of zero to represent a null pointer does not suffer from these disadvantages: it is pervasive, most programming languages treat zero as a special null value, and it has thoroughly proven its robustness.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] An exception is the way that zero participates in overload resolution in C++, where zero is treated as an integer rather than a pointer; for this reason the special value nullptr is preferred over the integer zero.
[src:memory-tagging-extension/tagged-pointer] However, with tagged pointers zeros are usually not used to represent null pointers.
